snippet.textDisplay:
The hotepery is strong with this one. Spending a year with billionaires is not guaranteed to turn you into a millionaire. Both Zuckerberg and Gates made their money by bringing innovation in tech. So unless you have a similar innovation being in their company can only do so much.
There is a wave of faux deepness spreading where turning down substantial cash in exchange for ‘knowledge’ is the smart way when the reality is that most millionaires have had financial help to get them on their way (a lot of those rags to riches stories are fabricated) and it is being ruthless and opportunistic that gets you riches not studying.
One millionaire can definitely be spent quickly if you have debt (nothing wrong with taking money to clear debt either) but if you have the means it can be wisely invested. Moreover, you could have a business idea that just needs to seed money snd then taking the money is your best option.

snippet.textDisplay:
DC is not the sharpest tool in the box but I totally side with him.

The women are operating out of fear and a need to rely on "proffesional" help for everything.

I have come across many people who simply don't know how to tidy their own house. 1girl I know pays someone to tidy her one bed flat. Others don't have such money so they live in constant mess.

That doesn't mean I am the same.
Comparing yourself to someone who has failed shows fear and lack of confidence in yourself to succeed.

Then you begin to think everyone else should be just as afraid as you to succeed. I am on the side of any responsible and well educated over thirty year old to make whatever decision suits them.

There is no wright or wrong.

There are people with all the intelligence and best business ideas in the world who will never ever ever see the fruition of their ideas not for lack of advice but for lack of a mill.

A fool is a fool. With or without a mill.
A wise man is the same. This debate is pointless.

Offering a mill to an under thirty is a risk. But if you have money to burn you can still do it.

Someone may totally abuse their first mill but then from that work extra hard never to take money for granted ever again.others may never learn.

Giving a mill to a materialistic over thirty who isn't very responsible is just as risky. But if you had money to burn why not do it?

If I was a trillionaire I would probably start by giving money to grandparents who have a chance to see mistakes they have made in life, they maybe aware of their imminent deaths and much wiser to re invest the money into their grand children than some parents.

I would start by giving to the elders and working my way down.

Age forces wisdom or a resignation to evil in my opinion.

Most elders would help out the younger generations and eliminate some of my need to give as I worked my way down.

The chances of adrenaline filled reckless and stupid energy/spending is much higher with the young.

The younger I go the more I would think about spending on the structures around the young such as family, education, community centres/reputable church youth groups/positive youth activities and such.

Ofcourse many young people can easily prove to be very wise with the money and many older people can prove to be quite stupid. Life is life.

There's no one size fits all with the human race. You just do whatever you think is best at the time innit.

But that's me. That's my two cent.
I am confident in my ability to seek guidance or to learn through google/youtube/libraries/the endless colleges and other adult education centres around london etc.

Give the milly and leave me in peace.

Just my 2 cents on the matter.

I
